      <field name="fulltext">THE TWO SABBATHS. The Song of Creation burst forth like the floods, That bow, as in worship, the rock-rooted woods;â Like streams of rejoicing the harmonies run, Uranus repeating the hymn of the Sunâ âThe work of Creation is finishedâis blestâ And Earth may enjoy her sweet Sabbath of rest!â Oh, listen!âthere mingles a murmur of woâ One note of complaining, so lengthened and low, It seems like the sigh of the flowers when flung, All fresh in their bloom, on the grave of the young; âThe moan is for man, wrung from Nature's sad breast; His sin has unhallowed her Sabbath of rest! The Song of Redemption flowed soft as the light, When turning to angels the spectres of night; The clouds wore an iris, the sunbeams a smile, As though in the chorus they chanted the whileâ âThe work of Redemption is hallowed above, And Earth may enjoy her sweet Sabbath of Love!â Oh, listen!âthe voices of Cherubim young Pour out their hosannas as incense is flung; No more from the world shall God's Spirit withdraw; The blood of the Cross blots the curse of the Law; And mortals below, and immortals above, Now hallow one Sabbathâthe Sabbath of Love!</field>
